Project Reflection
1. How did your prompt evolve across iterations?
My prompt evolved from a basic summarization task into a complex, constraint-based analytical engine within AI Studio. In Version 1, I simply asked the model to "Summarize the cyber incident and list next steps." The output was generic and critically failed to notice that the executive presentation contradicted the forensic report. By Version 2, I introduced a Chain-of-Thought (CoT) requirement, forcing the model to cross-reference timelines between the files. In Version 3, I finalized the prompt into a "Gold Standard" System Instruction with a strict JSON schema. I explicitly instructed the model to flag "Truth Conflicts," which successfully caught the discrepancy between the 91-hour GDPR notification delay in the report and the "immediate notification" claimed in the slides.

2. What model selection trade-offs did you observe?
I initially tested Gemini 1.5 Flash to optimize for speed and lower API costs. While Flash was incredibly fast at generating the UI schema, I observed a distinct "Optimism Bias." It tended to merge the optimistic tone of the Executive Slides with the Technical Report, smoothing over critical risks. I switched to Gemini 1.5 Pro. The trade-off was a slightly higher Time-to-First-Token (TTFT), but Pro demonstrated vastly superior reasoning. It successfully isolated the "MFA-Exempt" vulnerability in the report and flagged the Board Presentation's claim of "100% MFA Compliance" as a critical misrepresentation.

3. How did Stitch accelerate or constrain UX design?
Stitch drastically accelerated the wireframing process. By simply pasting my structured JSON output into Stitch, I was able to instantly generate a high-fidelity "Post-Incident Dashboard" featuring a dark-mode theme, a compliance warning widget, and a recovery timeline. However, Stitch also introduced constraints. I found that if my JSON schema was nested too deeply, the Stitch agent struggled to map the data to the UI cards accurately. This constrained my AI design, forcing me to flatten the JSON output in AI Studio so the Stitch UI could render the "Action Items" reliably without breaking the visual grid.

4. What would you change to productionise this system?
To move PIPA from a prototype to a production-ready system, I would implement three major changes. First, I would introduce Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) via Firebase Auth, allowing the CISO to see the raw technical risks while presenting a filtered, high-level view to the Board. Second, I would replace the manual PDF uploads in AI Studio with a live API integration into the company’s SIEM (Security Information and Event Management) and ticketing tools like Jira, so "Next Steps" are automatically assigned. Finally, I would deploy the backend to Cloud Run within a secure VPC (Virtual Private Cloud) to ensure that highly sensitive post-incident forensic data never traverses the public internet.
